        "exit-survey": {
            "kind": "exp-lookit-exit-survey",
            "doRecording": false,
            "debriefing": {
                "text": "Thank You for Participating! \n\nWe are interested in how children learn to talk about themselves! Sharing our thoughts, feelings, and experiences\u2014what we call 'self-disclosure'\u2014is more than just a common, everyday activity\u2014it's a complex skill! Unlike describing something in the physical world (like how a car engine works), talking about yourself requires you to look inward; you have to search through a 'database' of memories and feelings that only you can see. We want to characterize how this ability develops as children get older.\n\nPart 1: By asking your child to share 12 things about themselves with Karla, we are looking at what they choose to share, how many different topics they bring up, and how specific their details are.\n\nPart 2: By asking your child for 12 animals, we can get a general understanding of how children pull information from their memory. Specifically, we want to see if children pull animal names in a systematic manner (e.g., first 'farm animals' then 'ocean animals') that is different from how they pull information about themselves.\n\nWhy this matters: Even though people talk about themselves every day, scientists are still figuring out how this ability develops. By using new language-processing technology, we can turn children's disclosures into numerical data that helps us more precisely understand the developing mind.\n\nAs a thank you for your time, we will email you a $5 Amazon.com gift card within one week of participation. (Note: (1) one gift card per child, (2) your child must be in the age range for the study, and (3) your child must be visible during the study.)\n\nQuestions or Feedback? Please feel free to contact us at sll_lookit@stanford.edu."
            }
        },
